Used is where the value will be just gotta learn to give it the eyeball test. Check the action / string height off of the fretboard which determines how hard you have to press to fret a note. Look down the guitar level from the bridge to the headstock. Ideally the neck should be almost completely straight or a very small bow. Many old acoustics suffer from too much bow making them impossible to play past the 12th fret or so. A good guitar should some wiggle room left on the truss ross which you can use to adjust the neck curvature either way

Do you know how to play guitar "well enough" already?
If yes you always play the guitar to feel it out, do you like its sound; then check intonation, neck bow, fret buzz, neck twist. You'll be looking for something with solid wood soundboard, check quality of lining, neck joint and fret finish as they are indicators of well finished guitars.
With acoustic guitars you don't need to go for big brands like taylor or martin or baton rouge etc to get solid intermediate instruments, you can look around and see local manufacturers' models. Chinese stuff are getting really really good, Ayers and Naga are two of the brands you can check out. If you want to go big budget, a generalist instrument for fingerstylists is Taylor 414c/ce.
If you're just starting out, get a cheap guitar that has been set up well, still preferably with a hard top

Some of these are total cringe, like Ho Hey and Mumford.

--------
Of Monsters is basically a throwback to some post-grunge style from the 90s I forgot how it's called. It was done with trumpets and punkish pop jumpy melodies.

I found some songs from Romania like this:
https://youtu.be/DzOcZSox36M

I think it's probably from the Greenday era. They played this pop punk with trumpets, that is also something borrowed from Madness times.

------

"Best day of my life" is actually a good song, sure the style is cringe-hipster indie folk, but if you arranged the track with a different style, it would still sound good. It's a good pop song.

Home by Ed Sharp, also a good song. Same thing, it's couched in that hippie pastiche that was all the rage back then. But Ed Sh and the Magn Zeros are actually great live performers, they're no studio hacks. And they have a couple of good songs.

------

That indie folk style was cringe, sure, but it was the result of that decade zeitgeist. It was the post-financial crash decade, everything was gloom and doom. I guess it's the reflection of normies' being so addicted to positivity (the Polyanna principle), they'd adopt any form of escapism. And this indie folk stuff was a way to build yourself a useful mask of secure outward identity that exuded a positivity in complete contrast to what people were going through.

Sadly this became the foundation of a generation of zoomers who grew up with this fake-advertising atmospheres, for them this is how you should try to live every moment, by pretending everything is fine and great and you should look fresh and spiffy, as if you live perpetually in music video with people bubbling all around on the streets, being fashionable, fit and all upbeat.

This is really the most cancerous part of this culture, it has become a mindset. People actually living like this, always trying to project this facade and it's the result of that zeitgeist of which this music is a product.

They direct how the piece is supposed to sound. Like a pianist does with a piano but for an entire orchestra. So they decide the tempo and dynamics they want and the orchestra members all have to play that way simultaneously for it to sound good. They rehearse a lot beforehand and by the time they play the conductor is mostly there so no member forgets what they rehearsed the piece to sound like. Great conductors and orchestras can improvise those aspects of a piece on the spot if they are well in-tune.

>>114232925
Conducting is probably the single hardest job in the orchestra. Each instrumentalists only needs to know their part for any given piece. The conductor needs to know EVERY part, and he needs to know them inside and out. He uses one hand to provide a visual metronome to keep the players on time, and uses the other hand to simultaneously give directions to different sections about their expression (louder, quieter, more vibrato, etc.). Ultimately, the conductor is the one bringing all the different instrumentalists together and unifying their sound for the audience. It might look silly but it's a tough, tough job.

i didn't have lessons but i was absolutely consumed by the instrument for most of that time, i mean i had to practice in the shed during winter because of my family and i'd stay out there until 3-4am every day, something in me just hated the idea of not learning the instrument. i was 17 when i started and i was afraid that i started too late, which i probably did, but i'm finally getting to a point where i'm more and more satisfied with my tone production.

it's easy to draw the bow over the string but in the beginning you don't really have the muscles needed to really control the bow, you're just sort of dragging it, and it will be hard to have nice long bow strokes. the thing about playing in tune is that even if it's an open string you can still be out of tune because the bow can alter the pitch, so in the beginning, when you have inconsistent bow speed, you end up with a sound that goes up and down and sounds awful. i'm not saying you can't do it but i definitely couldn't for at least the first 2-3 years. that's how long it took me to get a consistent tone out of my violin.

>>114184516
some cool sound design in this, you are talented. there are some mix issues that i probably wouldn't be able to describe without sitting down with you and looking at the project itself. the percussion feels weak; part of the weakness is in the mixing, another part is in the arrangement/stylistic choices. a sampled break would do wonders for the tune; when working entirely synths, tempering the synthetic nature with the character of live percussion can really do wonders. as for the synths, it feels like there's some gnarly resonance in the mid-high region. it's really, really tough to mix an entirely-synth track well. judicious use of eq and bell filters to make each synth track occupy its own distinct place in the mix could be useful. panning is also a hidden dimension through which space can be carved out. pic related; it's from an ancient textbook on mixing, but a useful way to think about space in a mix; 3 axes: volume, frequency, and stereo field. tldr, would focus on mixing fundamentals: eq and parallel compression. good track.

anyone with even the slightest hint of an inclination towards an engineering mindset would immediately be able to tell you that that's a nearly intractable problem. think about, in the ideal, best conditions, how something like that might work. what assumptions would the system need to make about your intent with the song? assuming it can make those assumptions, how is it able to determine what tracks are actually what? (way less possible in the 90s than today.) i'm assuming your father is not a dummy, and there's probably a misunderstanding/miscommunication.

i suppose he could be talking about a system which, given raw, unnormalized tracks, normalizes them to a similar RMS or LUFS value. that certainly would have been possible, but probably would not have yielded listenable or good results, and is hardly "mixing" in the sense it's commonly understood.

In my opinion, the goal of sample-flipping should be to use the lightest possible touch. Because with enough processing, it is possible to get similar results out of extremely different sound sources. I've used a recording I made of my washing machine and flipped it into a pad instrument that could have probably been achieved with literally any other sample, because the processing was extremely elaborate, so the original character of the sample was nearly absent.

Do you like Phil Collins? I've been a big Genesis fan ever since the release of their 1980 album, Duke. Before that, I really didn't understand any of their work. Too artsy, too intellectual. It was on Duke where Phil Collins' presence became more apparent. I think Invisible Touch was the group's undisputed masterpiece. It's an epic meditation on intangibility. At the same time, it deepens and enriches the meaning of the preceding three albums. Christy, take off your robe. Listen to the brilliant ensemble playing of Banks, Collins and Rutherford. You can practically hear every nuance of every instrument. Sabrina, remove your dress. In terms of lyrical craftsmanship, the sheer songwriting, this album hits a new peak of professionalism. Sabrina, why don't you, uh, dance a little. Take the lyrics to Land of Confusion. In this song, Phil Collins addresses the problems of abusive political authority. In Too Deep is the most moving pop song of the 1980s, about monogamy and commitment. The song is extremely uplifting. Their lyrics are as positive and affirmative as anything I've heard in rock. Christy, get down on your knees so Sabrina can see your asshole. Phil Collins' solo career seems to be more commercial and therefore more satisfying, in a narrower way. Especially songs like In the Air Tonight and Against All Odds. Sabrina, don't just stare at it, eat it. But I also think Phil Collins works best within the confines of the group, than as a solo artist, and I stress the word artist. This is Sussudio, a great, great song, a personal favorite.

I think the first record is too difficult a listen to be more than a contrarian choice for the best- you have to already have acquired a strong taste for that kind of abrasive - stuff like early La Dispute or As Cities Burn is a lot more enjoyable without sacraficing songcraft or technicality.

Three Cheers is where the band reaches their stride, and when the highest highs of their songwriting was reached, but to say that the Black Parade is bad when these records are cut from the same cloth is disingenuous. There are no really weak tracks on The Black Parade, Teenagers being the contender for worst, but it's still a decent song. Three Cheers sort of has a weak patch near the end, it's less consistent. The fact that the Black Parade is accessible (again, so is Three Cheers) or that it seems to take influence from bands like Aerosmith with some of the slow songs doesn't make it worse, necessarily.

On that note, the theatrical aspects are why I compared it to >>114223697 Say Anything or that it fit in with records like American Idiot. It's not that MCR is a pop punk band, but that there is serious overlap in the target audience- it represented a trend for increasing effort in Pop Punk to ascend beyond the alleged shallow vapid formulaic stereotypes of the genre, and of musical theatre influence percolating in. This period also saw Marianas Trench's Masterpiece Theatre, which has Queen influence and big medleys, or Blink 182 trying to grow up on their Self-Titled. Bands were suddenly making front to back albums and crafting longer songs, or slow songs that weren't the one acoustic song on the album.

T. Pop punk historian

In USA, it's not uncommon for people to be unfamiliar with classical music, or to have trouble distinguishing between different Scandinavian countries. However, that doesn't mean that the influence of classical music on electronic music subgenres in these countries should be overlooked.

In the case of dungeon synth, a subgenre of electronic music that originated in the 1980s and 1990s, it's interesting to consider the distinct musical influences that have shaped its development in different parts of Scandinavia.

For example, in Sweden, it's been suggested that the keyboard and organ music of ABBA, the iconic Swedish pop group, had a significant influence on the development of dungeon synth in the country. ABBA's music is known for its catchy and upbeat sound, and it's not surprising that it would have an impact on other musical genres.

On the other hand, in Norway, it's been suggested that the music of composer Grieg had a greater influence on the development of dungeon synth. Grieg was a 19th century Norwegian composer known for his romantic and nationalistic style, and his music often featured prominent piano and orchestral elements.

While these two examples may seem quite different at first glance, it's worth noting that the use of organs and keyboards is a common feature in both ABBA's music and dungeon synth, and it's possible that this shared element contributed to the influence of ABBA's music on Swedish dungeon synth.

Overall, it's fascinating to consider the various musical influences that have shaped the development of different subgenres of electronic music, and how these influences can vary from one country to another.

Grim was the world and grey last night:
The moon and stars were fled,
The hall was dark without song or light,
The fires were fallen dead.
The wind in the trees was like to the sea,
And over the mountains' teeth
It whistled bitter-cold and free,
As a sword leapt from its sheath.

The lord of snows upreared his head;
His mantle long and pale
Upon the bitter blast was spread
And hung o'er hill and dale.
The world was blind,
the boughs were bent,
All ways and paths were wild:
Then the veil of cloud apart was rent,
And here was born a Child.

The ancient dome of heaven sheer
Was pricked with distant light;
A star came shining white and clear
Alone above the night.
In the dale of dark in that hour of birth
One voice on a sudden sang:
Then all the bells in Heaven and Earth
Together at midnight rang.

Mary sang in this world below:
They heard her song arise
O’er mist and over mountain snow
To the walls of Paradise,
And the tongue of many bells was stirred
in Heaven's towers to ring
When the voice of mortal maid was heard,
That was mother of Heaven's King.

Glad is the world and fair this night
With stars about its head,
And the hall is filled with laughter and light,
And fires are burning red.
The bells of Paradise now ring
With bells of Christendom,
And Gloria, Gloria we will sing
That God on earth is come.

Dungeon synth is a style of Electronic music that focuses on evoking epic, atmospheric soundscapes associated with fantasy and medieval settings. Artists primarily utilize synthesizers, keyboards, and drum machines to create Ambient and orchestral textures, with vocals, samples, acoustic instruments, and lo-fi production also occasionally employed. Due to its instrumental nature, dungeon synth musicians concentrate on storytelling through music and create specific sceneries often inspired by mythology, literature of fantasy writers such as J.R.R. Tolkien, video games, and tabletop RPGs like Dungeons & Dragons. The term was coined on March 17th, 2011, in Andrew Werdna's first post on Dungeon Synth Blog, where he described it as "the sound of the ancient crypt."

Early influences of the genre include Berlin School acts such as Tangerine Dream and Klaus Schulze creating layered, synthesizer-led textures inspired by space and futurism. Jim Kirkwood took these hypnotic soundscapes and used them to produce fantasy-oriented atmospheres. Another wave of influence came from the Neoclassical Darkwave sound of Dead Can Dance, who developed their compositions using synths and drum machines. Dark Ambient and Martial Industrial were also important influences, as plenty of early examples of dungeon synth were guided by those styles.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=85I6tnjsb9I
The first dungeon synth artists emerged in the early-mid 1990s in the wake of the Norwegian Black Metal scene. Mortiis started his solo career after he departed from Emperor and embraced simply-produced, medieval-esque compositions. Varg Vikernes often utilized ambient/dungeon synth interludes on Burzum records, and after his imprisonment, he released his two "prison albums," Dauði Baldrs and Hliðskjálf, which were recorded using a synthesizer and a tape recorder. Other significant projects from the first era include Depressive Silence, who dabbled in ethereal, lush, and lo-fi soundscapes, and Summoning, who accentuated their Symphonic Black Metal sound with keyboards and drum machines.

In the 2000s, dungeon synth experienced a decline, where acts discontinued or went in different directions with their style. The genre began regaining interest in the early 2010s, with blogs and sites such as Andrew Werdna's Dungeon Synth Blog and the Dungeon Synth Archives Youtube channel introducing the genre to new listeners. Werdna's Blog in particular helped establish a more formal description of its sound. Projects which contributed to the revival wave, such as Erang, Lord Lovidicus, and Fief, were inspired by the 1990s acts, while Bandcamp became the successor to the tape trading community. Due to its rising popularity in the late 2010s and 2020s, dungeon synth artists began experimenting with creating different, more specific moods with Winter Synth (Yearner, Inoriand) exploring cold soundscapes while Comfy Synth (Grandma's Cottage, Earthencloak) delved into cozy, nostalgic atmospheres, dropping the epic aesthetic.

So I began searching for a recording device but couldn't find one. I keep many but could not find one. At least I couldn't find any modern digital USB and easy but I found a freestyle with built in mic and rec function and used it. Not very good quality. I played a string instrument that I keep and got it flowing. A nice raga riff over e and a. A meditative riff. I listened to the recording and most quality was lost but some tape magic was gained. Will probably overdub it with proper sounds and make it work. This got me thinking about this thing that has been around my head this complete dsd. Those 90s DS tapes we like to collect and remember. Many of those. Almost half of those where aquatic, ritualised and primal. Often primitive room recordings and two deck overdubs and all that. A lot of magical moments. What I was thinking is that these are very hard to redo and repete. Not becouse we lack inspiration and that youthful creativity but becouse our technology. Many techniques of yesteryears are unthought of today becouse we got these computers with track mixers built in. The most primitive we can think of is a tape porta or something. If we try to copy the techniques of old (two tape secs and a mixer for overdubs as an example) it would just be silly and stupid. Why would we. And downgrading quantity with vsts and effects are even more el Retardo. Yes. This is what I've been thinking. Thank you.

>>114239676
Their idea of "Theory of Phonetic Organization" is pretty good, and it’s best put here. It states, "the musician should put the sounds first, building the music up from them rather than developing the music, then working down to the sounds that make it up."
Basically, they played around with instruments and things, and after finding sounds they thought sounded cool, they used them to make songs. They did not write music and then decide on what instruments to play it on.
What this captures is the feeling of fucking around with instruments. I play a bit of guitar, and I spend a lot of time just fucking around with funny noises I find, and I generally think “this sounds cool in the moment, but I’d never record and release this.” The Residents though, they did just that. And since it was a group, and they didn’t even know how to play any instruments on the album, it has this air of loose experimentation that could also be called soul.
I feel like, with time, the Residents have become stuck in some ways, a lot of their albums all sound pretty similar to each other. But their early work, every single album is really cool

I was actually disappointed that the theories around a companion "Nation" album didn't end up being true, as the idea of two companion albums combining to make "Damnation" is leagues better than "its meant to be played in reverse and its called "Damn" cause "wow damn, lol"". Plus, Kendrick claiming that this album was his best material is even more delusional than the black israelite preaching at the outro of that Fear song. Kendrick sounded depressed on this material and it comes across with how unfocused and flat alot of the material felt.

Feel, Pride, Lust, Fear and Duckworth are good, everything else is forgettable imo. Mr. Morale like the actually good version of what this album was trying to be. 5/10 album.

they got a wierd run from Dookie to American Idiot, you'd though that maybe AI would been more appealing as a very late 90's album or very early 2000's album.

Everything else sort of makes sense as Queen-type-Stadium-Rock-Alternative-Rock-Band-Music but American Idiot was sort of the last breath of Old-School Green Day and sort of gets wacked by the image and weird packaging of the music.
